  "integration_blocked_until": "operator posts HNOTE-DESIGN-REFRESH-PHASE-A-INTEGRATION-APPROVED-NNN in monitor/decisions/human-notes.json with approved_exp_ids containing 'EXP-202'",
  "human_note_source": "HNOTE-DESIGN-REFRESH-PHASE-A-001",
  "companion_note": "HNOTE-DESIGN-REFRESH-ROUTING-001",
  "target": "docs/index.html <head> and <style> :root block (dark media query mirror). Also touches: build-scripts/generate-html.js only if that file owns head injection (it does — verify before integration).",
  "category": "design-refresh-phase-a",
  "scope_item": "Item 6 foundation — typography tokens + Google Fonts load (EXP-A1 in the suggested brief sequence). Also supplies --ink, --ink-2, --rule, --accent, --warn, --crit, --good tokens required by subsequent EXPs.",
  "priority": "high",
  "source": "HNOTE-DESIGN-REFRESH-PHASE-A-001 section 'SUGGESTED EXP ORDERING' step EXP-A1; item enumerated under SCOPE Items 6 (typography) and 7 (palette, which depends on tokens existing before restriction is applied).",
  "curmudgeon_review": null,
  "created_at": "2026-04-21T12:05:01.171Z",
  "kernel_of_truth": "The external designer is right that our current CSS leans entirely on one system-sans face ('Segoe UI',Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif) for body, UI chrome, and prose, and that the formulas are plain monospace without a class. That single-face-does-every-job pattern makes the site read as a dashboard rather than as an argumentative document. A three-role typographic system (serif for prose, sans for chrome, mono for data evidence) is a mature, well-understood pattern in editorial design, and the site gains credibility by adopting the same convention long-form argumentative publications use. The reviewer is also right that tokenizing the palette (--ink, --rule, --crit, etc.) is a prerequisite for the Item 7 red-restriction work — you cannot cleanly restrict red usage until there is a single token that declares where red is allowed. Conceding those two points is free and does not require conceding the paper-theme aesthetic the reviewer's mocks use.",
  "content_diff": {
    "description": "Two additive changes to docs/index.html. No existing selectors are removed or redefined. No existing font-family declarations are changed in this EXP (that is EXP-A2). No existing colors are remapped (that is EXP-A5). Purely introduces new tokens and loads the webfonts so subsequent EXPs can consume them.",
    "change_1_google_fonts_preconnect_and_stylesheet": {
      "where": "docs/index.html inside <head>, immediately after the existing <meta name=viewport ...> tag and before the first <style> block.",
      "rationale": "preconnect issues the DNS+TLS handshake early so the font CSS fetch does not block first paint. display=swap lets the existing system-sans face render first and swap in the webface when ready (no FOUT blank text).",
      "exact_insert": "<link rel=\"preconnect\" href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com\"><link rel=\"preconnect\" href=\"https://fonts.gstatic.com\" crossorigin><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Source+Serif+4:ital,opsz,wght@0,8..60,400;0,8..60,600;0,8..60,700;1,8..60,400&family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap\" rel=\"stylesheet\">",
      "weight_set_justification": "Serif loads italic + 400/600/700 for body/emphasis/headings. Inter loads 400/500/600/700 for UI chrome (captions at 500, pills at 600, small-caps kickers at 700). Mono loads 400/500 for code + subtle data emphasis. Any weight asked for by the final type spec and not in this set would fall back to the nearest loaded weight — if EXP-A2 requires weights outside this set, this EXP's weight list should be updated rather than loading them one-off elsewhere."
    },
    "change_2_new_design_tokens_in_root": {
      "where": "docs/index.html inside the :root{...} declaration at the top of the <style> block. Add new tokens at the end of the existing declaration (do NOT modify or remove any of --bg, --text, --heading, --accent, --link, --border, --table-header, --refuted*, --stdmodel*, --selfcon*, --misleading*, --unfalsifiable*, --notdemo*, --code-bg, --card-bg — those stay for backward compatibility with every selector that already consumes them).",
      "rationale": "Additive tokenization. The existing verdict-color tokens remain authoritative for verdict pills and table cells; Item 7 palette restriction in EXP-A5 will route them through the new semantic tokens. The new tokens give EXP-A2 (typography application), EXP-A5 (red restriction), and EXP-A8 (a11y contrast tuning) a single source of truth to edit.",
      "new_tokens_root_light": {
        "--serif": "'Source Serif 4', Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif",
        "--sans": "'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system, 'Segoe UI', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif",
        "--mono": "'JetBrains Mono', ui-monospace, 'SF Mono', Consolas, 'Courier New', monospace",
        "--ink": "#181715",
        "--ink-2": "#3A352D",
        "--ink-3": "#6E675B",
        "--rule": "#E4DDCB",
        "--semantic-accent": "#1e5f8a",
        "--semantic-accent-soft": "#d8e8f2",
        "--semantic-warn": "#8a5a1e",
        "--semantic-warn-soft": "#f3e6d3",
        "--semantic-crit": "#7a2e2e",
        "--semantic-crit-soft": "#f2dada",
        "--semantic-good": "#2e5a2e",
        "--semantic-good-soft": "#d9ead9"
      },
      "new_tokens_dark_override": {
        "where": "inside @media(prefers-color-scheme:dark){:root{...}} — add new overrides at end of that block alongside the existing ones.",
        "--ink": "#e8e6e1",
        "--ink-2": "#b8b5ad",
        "--ink-3": "#8a8680",
        "--rule": "#2e2e4a",
        "--semantic-accent": "#7eb8da",
        "--semantic-accent-soft": "#2a4a65",
        "--semantic-warn": "#d99860",
        "--semantic-warn-soft": "#3d2e20",
        "--semantic-crit": "#d46a6a",
        "--semantic-crit-soft": "#3d1f1f",
        "--semantic-good": "#7aa87a",
        "--semantic-good-soft": "#1f2e1f"
      },
      "new_tokens_print_override": {
        "where": "inside @media print{:root{...}} — same override list as the light root, mirrored. Print output should match the ink-on-paper aesthetic of the existing PDF pipeline.",
        "note": "Print tokens are identical to light-root tokens, so the same dictionary applies. No new print-only values."
      },
      "naming_rationale": "--semantic-* prefix on accent/warn/crit/good/etc is chosen to avoid colliding with the existing --accent variable, which is consumed by many selectors and is NOT being remapped in this EXP. EXP-A5 will be responsible for renaming/migrating consumers; EXP-A1 stays additive. Once EXP-A5 completes the migration, the analyst can request a follow-up to drop the --semantic- prefix; this is left for that EXP's scope."
    },
    "change_3_no_changes_to": [
      "Existing body { font-family: 'Segoe UI', ... } declaration — stays. EXP-A2 replaces it.",
      "Existing font-family:monospace literals (3 in sections.json, more in docs/index.html) — stay. EXP-A2 migrates them to a .formula class.",
      "Existing verdict color tokens (--refuted, --stdmodel, etc.) — stay. EXP-A5 will migrate them to route through --semantic-crit / --semantic-good / etc. where appropriate.",
      "Existing .title-block, .scorecard, .verdict-legend, .vl-* selectors — stay. No visual change from this EXP.",
      "test.js — no new assertions this EXP. EXP-A2 will add 'font-family:monospace literal count is 0' once migration is done.",
      "build-scripts/generate-html.js — already emits the <head> block; if the head template lives in that file, the preconnect + stylesheet inserts go there and are copied through to docs/index.html on build. Verify location before integration."
    ]
  },
  "acceptance_criteria": [
    "View-source on docs/index.html shows the three <link> tags for preconnect + Google Fonts stylesheet in <head>.",
    "DevTools Computed panel on any element shows the new :root variables (--serif, --sans, --mono, --ink, --ink-2, --ink-3, --rule, --semantic-accent, --semantic-warn, --semantic-crit, --semantic-good, and their -soft counterparts) available for use.",
    "DevTools Network panel shows Source Serif 4 + Inter + JetBrains Mono WOFF2 files downloaded exactly once per page load.",
    "Visual regression: the page looks IDENTICAL before and after this EXP (no selectors consume the new tokens yet, body font-family is unchanged).",
    "Integrity's build-reproducibility check passes unchanged (fresh clone + node build.js html produces byte-identical docs/index.html up to the embedded date line).",
    "test.js passes at the current baseline (no new assertions from this EXP).",
    "No console errors. No CORS errors. No layout shift."
  ],
  "anticipated_objections": [
    {
      "objection": "Adding webfonts for a 'no visual change' EXP wastes bandwidth on users who will never see them (because nothing consumes --serif/--sans/--mono yet).",
      "response": "True in the interval between EXP-A1 integration and EXP-A2 integration. Mitigated by: (a) the suggested sequence lands EXP-A2 immediately after EXP-A1, (b) display=swap means the fonts never block render, (c) WOFF2 with preconnect costs roughly 60–90 KB on cold load — acceptable for the architectural benefit of having tokens and fonts land as a single foundation rather than a bundled megadiff. Alternative considered: roll EXP-A1 and EXP-A2 together. Rejected because A2 is a large prose-file migration (font-family:monospace → .formula literals across sections.json and index.html) that deserves an independent review window."
    },
    {
      "objection": "Privacy: Google Fonts makes a third-party request and logs user IP, which is a regression if the site is currently self-contained.",
      "response": "Legitimate concern. Current docs/index.html makes zero third-party requests. Adding Google Fonts breaks that property. Two mitigations the human review group should weigh: (a) self-host the three WOFF2 files under docs/fonts/ and declare @font-face locally — avoids the third-party request entirely, costs ~6 weight files to commit, adds a new build step to copy/check-hash the fonts; (b) use Bunny Fonts (GDPR-compliant, IP-scrubbed proxy for Google Fonts) as a drop-in CDN replacement — zero self-host overhead, keeps display=swap. Recommendation: flag this in notes_for_human_review_group and let the operator pick. Default in this EXP is Google Fonts with display=swap; flip to self-host with one <link> replacement if the group prefers."
    },
    {
      "objection": "The --semantic-* prefix pollutes the token namespace. Why not overwrite --accent, --warn, etc. directly?",
      "response": "Because --accent is already consumed by many existing selectors, and overwriting it changes visual output across the whole site. That is EXP-A5's job, not EXP-A1's. Keeping the prefix separates 'introduce the new tokens' from 'migrate consumers to them'. After EXP-A5, the analyst may propose a cleanup renaming --semantic-crit → --crit (etc.) — that is tracked in out_of_scope_for_this_exp and deferred to a post-A5 cleanup EXP."
    },
    {
      "objection": "Four new --ink-* tokens is one too many — why --ink-3?",
      "response": "Three roles (ink / ink-2 / ink-3 = primary / secondary / faint) match the external reviewer's own mock, which distinguishes body copy from meta/caption from faint metadata (the eyebrow kicker color). EXP-A2 will map them to actual text classes. If A2 finds --ink-3 has no consumer, the analyst can drop it as cleanup; landing it here costs nothing and avoids a token-addition churn in A2."
    },
    {
      "objection": "You are introducing palette tokens tuned for dark theme but also defining light-theme values. The site only displays dark; the light values are dead weight.",
      "response": "The site currently has a :root light default AND an @media(prefers-color-scheme:dark) override, AND a @media print override. PDF output runs in the light/print pathway. Not defining light-theme values would break print rendering the moment any consumer selector landed in A2. The cost of the light-theme dictionary is ~120 bytes of CSS."
    }
  ],
