  "notes_for_human_review_group": [
    "PRIVACY DEFAULT: this draft uses Google Fonts. If the group prefers zero third-party requests, say the word and a revision will swap to self-hosted WOFF2 in docs/fonts/ (adds three ~30KB files to the repo and one build-step copy). Bunny Fonts is a third option (GDPR proxy, same URL shape, one-line swap).",
    "FONT WEIGHTS loaded here (Source Serif 4 italic+400/600/700, Inter 400/500/600/700, JetBrains Mono 400/500) are a prediction about what EXP-A2 will need. If A2's prose audit finds we need e.g. Inter 300 for very-faint metadata or Source Serif 4 900 for display weight, this EXP's weight list should be revised before or at A2 integration rather than loading the extra weights from A2. Flagging so the group knows the cost of the revision is 'edit the href, no re-audit' — small.",
    "--ink-3 is speculative. It is in this draft because the external reviewer's mock uses three ink tiers. If EXP-A2's prose audit finds no consumer for the third tier, the analyst recommends dropping --ink-3 as part of A2's cleanup rather than amending A1 after the fact.",
    "SEMANTIC PREFIX DECISION: --semantic-accent / --semantic-warn / --semantic-crit / --semantic-good is verbose. The rationale is in anticipated_objection #3. Group may prefer a shorter prefix (e.g. --s-accent) or no prefix at all (overwriting --accent et al. in this EXP and doing the consumer migration in A5 as a big-bang). The analyst's default is the safer additive path; if the group prefers the big-bang, flip the rename and A5 subsumes the migration.",
    "BUNDLING WITH A2: if the group prefers a single-EXP foundation-plus-application, the analyst can collapse A1+A2 into one draft. Cost: larger review surface, harder to back out typography without also ripping out tokens. Kept separate here for reversibility.",
    "PRINT PATHWAY: the current print override inherits from :root light values. If the group intends PDF output to also adopt the serif-body aesthetic (it probably should, since the external review's mock IS paper/serif), that is a natural EXP-A2 extension to the print path. Not in scope here, but flagging it so it doesn't get missed."
  ],
